## Device Identity & PKI Authentication (Layer 1)

**Challenge-Response Protocol** (prevents replay attacks):

```rust
// Device registration
pub struct DeviceIdentity {
    device_id: DeviceId,              // Unique identifier
    public_key: PublicKey,             // Ed25519 for signatures
    certificates: Vec<X509Certificate>, // DoD PKI chain
    device_type: DeviceType,           // UAV, UGV, C2, etc.
    organization: OrganizationUnit,    // AUKUS partner
}

// Authentication flow
1. Device → Server: HELLO (device_id, public_key)
2. Server → Device: CHALLENGE (nonce)
3. Device → Server: RESPONSE (signature(nonce, private_key))
4. Server verifies: signature matches public_key in certificate
```

**DoD PKI Integration:**

- X.509 certificate chain validation
- Certificate Revocation List (CRL) checking
- Offline operation with pre-provisioned CRLs

---

## Role-Based Authorization (Layer 4)

**Five roles** aligned with military operations:

| Role | Permissions | Use Case |
|------|-------------|----------|
| **Leader** | Command cell, set objectives, tactical decisions | Squad/Platoon leader |
| **Member** | Advertise capabilities, join/leave, execute commands | Platform (UAV/UGV) |
| **Observer** | Read-only access, no command authority | Intelligence analyst |
| **Commander** | Direct multiple cells, strategic decisions | Company/Battalion HQ |
| **Admin** | System configuration, user management | IT support, DevOps |

**Policy Enforcement:**

```rust
// Example: Only Leaders can issue movement commands
fn authorize_command(user: &User, command: &Command) -> Result<()> {
    match command.command_type {
        CommandType::Movement => {
            require_role(user, Role::Leader)?;
        },
        CommandType::Report => {
            require_role(user, Role::Member)?; // Any member can report
        },
        CommandType::SystemConfig => {
            require_role(user, Role::Admin)?;
        },
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

